  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Psalm 74:3",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 74:3",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Lift up thy feet — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This is spoken after the manner of men, and means, Come speedily to our rescue, and do not delay, as men do when they sit or stand still; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "unto — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Or rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "because of, the perpetual desolations — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Namely, those ruins of the city and country, which had lasted so very long, and which, if God did not come to their help, he intimates, would be perpetual and irrecoverable. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Even all that the enemy hath done wickedly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — God had deserted his sanctuary, and the shechinah, or cloud of glory, emblematical of the divine presence, had gone up from between the cherubim: see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 10:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In consequence of which the heathen people had invaded that holy place, and laid it waste. And the psalmist here supplicates and urges God’s return to them, as that which alone could restore their temple, city, and country to their former happy state.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
